<TITLE> BCB Academy team leaves for Australia Thursday </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 19 (bdnews24.com)  The Bangladesh Cricket Board (BCB) Academy team leaves for Australia Thursday to take part in two tournamentsthe Institute Challenge Cup and the Crocodile Cup in Darwin, Australia. The academy boys will play four one-dayers in the Institute Challenge Cup and will then fight it out in the Crocodile Cup where they will play three matchesone dayer and as many three-dayer and four-dayer. "I understand that our opponents are good sides," coach-cum-manager Khaled Mahmud told reporters at a news conference at the Sher-e-Bangla National Stadium Sunday. "You can say the boys will play against the second string teams of Australian states, which comprise promising players as well as first-class cricketers," said the former Bangladesh skipper. Academy skipper Mehrab Hossain Junior said the players with over 10,000 first-class runs will feature in the Northern Territory side. "Wet weather is now prevailing in the southern region of Australia and most of the southern region cricketers come to play in Darwin. "I was in Darwin two years back and saw the players having over 10,000 first-class run playing there. So there is no doubt about the strength of our opponents." The BCB Academy team will play against Western Australia, New South Wales, Queensland Academy of Sports and Australian Capital Territory in the Institute Challenge Cup. Tasmania and Northern Territory Strike will be the Bangladesh's opponents in the Crocodile Cup. The team is scheduled to return home on September 15. bdnew
